2026-04-03 | Maximum Walls Destroyed by Robots

	Question
Choose direction for each robot to maximize number of destroyed walls.

	Key Observations
1.	Robots block bullets → act as boundaries  
2.	Each robot independently chooses direction  
3.	We should avoid double-counting walls  
4.	Greedy choice per robot works because:
		robots don’t interfere except blocking  

	Approach
1.	Sort robots and walls.  
2.	For each robot:
		find nearest robot on left and right  

3.	Compute:
		left range:
			max(robot[i] - distance[i], prevRobot + 1)  
		right range:
			min(robot[i] + distance[i], nextRobot - 1)

4.	Count walls in both ranges using binary search.  

5.	Pick direction with maximum walls.  

6.	Mark walls as used (to avoid duplicates).  

	Time Complexity
	O(n log n + m log m)

	Space Complexity
	O(m)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    int maxWallsDestroyed(vector<int>& robots,
                          vector<int>& distance,
                          vector<int>& walls) {

        int n = robots.size();
        sort(walls.begin(), walls.end());

        vector<pair<int,int>> r;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
            r.push_back({robots[i], distance[i]});

        sort(r.begin(), r.end());

        unordered_set<int> destroyed;

        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){

            int pos = r[i].first;
            int dist = r[i].second;

            int leftLimit = pos - dist;
            int rightLimit = pos + dist;

            if(i > 0)
                leftLimit = max(leftLimit, r[i-1].first + 1);

            if(i < n-1)
                rightLimit = min(rightLimit, r[i+1].first - 1);

            // count left
            int l = lower_bound(walls.begin(), walls.end(), leftLimit) - walls.begin();
            int r1 = upper_bound(walls.begin(), walls.end(), pos) - walls.begin();

            int leftCount = 0;
            for(int j=l;j<r1;j++){
                if(!destroyed.count(walls[j]))
                    leftCount++;
            }

            // count right
            int l2 = lower_bound(walls.begin(), walls.end(), pos) - walls.begin();
            int r2 = upper_bound(walls.begin(), walls.end(), rightLimit) - walls.begin();

            int rightCount = 0;
            for(int j=l2;j<r2;j++){
                if(!destroyed.count(walls[j]))
                    rightCount++;
            }

            // choose best direction
            if(leftCount >= rightCount){
                for(int j=l;j<r1;j++)
                    destroyed.insert(walls[j]);
            } else {
                for(int j=l2;j<r2;j++)
                    destroyed.insert(walls[j]);
            }
        }

        return destroyed.size();
    }
};

	Key Insight
Each robot has **two independent choices** (left/right), but robots act as **barriers**.  

So we:
- restrict each robot’s shooting interval  
- greedily pick the direction that destroys more *new* walls  

This ensures maximum unique wall destruction.
